[1] Estonia
Date: Fri 25 Jan 2013
Source: Rosselkhoznadzor, Russia's Federal Service for Veterinary and Phytosanitary Surveillance/News [machine transl., edited]
http://fsvps.ru/fsvps/news/5924.html


About the alleged large-scale outbreak of the disease caused by Schmallenberg virus in Estonia
-------------------------------------
According to obtained information, lambs with congenital malformations, characteristic of the disease caused by the Schmallenberg virus, have been recorded in Estonia.

As known, the virus is widespread in the EU, which has not taken any measures to control and eradicate the disease. Moreover, since the end of May 2012 the virus was officially declared endemic in the EU countries in which the disease was initially reported. Since no official SBV reports are required, information about the SBV situation is no longer accessible.

Rosselkhoznadzor has reason to believe that undeclared outbreaks occurred in other European countries, particularly in the Czech Republic and Hungary. Since introduction of breeding animals, infected with SBV, from Austria to Russia and Kazakhstan has been monitored while the EU veterinary services are inactive, this strongly suggests an increased risk of introduction of the virus into the territory of the Customs Union.

Rosselkhoznadzor considers it necessary to request information from the veterinary services of a number of EU countries, including Estonia, Lithuania, Latvia and Poland, about the detection of SBV cases in these countries. Information is requested on the measures used in the case of seropositive and PCR-positive animals, and on the control exercised upon the movement of animals from countries or regions in which SBV is detected.

--
