[The final report of the last General session of the OIE, Paris, May 2012, includes the following statement (art 244):

"The Director General thanked all the countries affected by SBV for notifying infections, in a timely manner, as an emerging disease. After end of May 2012, affected Member Countries that so desired could send a final report and consider the disease endemic*. The information published by the OIE on the safe trade of commodities and animals would be further updated as more information became available. More scientific research was needed on SBV and other viruses in the same family found in other countries of the world.

"He reminded the Assembly that revised criteria for the listing of diseases were being presented for adoption at the present General Session, indicating that this disease would not be eligible for the listing according to these revised criteria. After end of May 2012, affected Member Countries that so desired could send a final report and consider the disease endemic. The information published by the OIE on the safe trade of commodities and animals would be further updated as more information became available. More scientific research was needed on SBV and other viruses in the same family found in other countries of the world."

*The following 9 European countries, which initially notified SBV as an emerging disease, have submitted final reports in which they declared that the event was resolved and that no more reports will be submitted:

Country/ date final report/ Total outbreaks as of date of final report
Belgium/ 22 May 2012/ 15
France/ 22 May 2012/ 1471
Germany/ 30 May 2012/ 1376
Italy/ 22 May 2012/ 1
Luxembourg/ 2 Apr 2012/ 12
Netherlands/ 1 Jun 2012/ 345
Spain/ 22 May 2012/ 1
Switzerland / 10 Aug 2012/ 19
UK/ 22 May 2012/ 266

Other countries known or believed at present to be SBV-infected are: Austria, the Czech Republic, Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Ireland, Northern Ireland, Norway, Poland, and Sweden. In Italy, Sardinia has been added with multiple outbreaks. Slovenia is suspected as well (see item 2 further).

The most recent meeting of EU's Standing Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health (SCFCAH) which had, on its agenda, SBV, was held in Brussels on 5 Jun 2012. The report of the said meeting included the following statement: "The importance for the EU to continue in its transparency policy was stressed and, therefore, Member States were encouraged to continue providing data to EFSA enabling the issuance of future updates by them." Such updates, if becoming publicly available (e.g., in EU's SBV web-site http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/schmallenberg_virus/index_en.htm) would have enhanced transparency.

EFSA published on Nov 2012 an analysis with an overview of the "SBV situation after 1 year" (reporting period from 1 Aug 2011 till 31 Jul 2012), together with an update of newly affected herds. The document was reviewed in posting 20121124.1422556. - Mod.AS]

