[While the Australian experience with Akabane virus and its control is of paramount value, its applicability in Europe, in relation to SBV, might be in need of modifications. Where Akabane virus is constantly present, animals usually become infected before their 1st pregnancy; clinical signs do not occur in their offspring. Clinical cases are usually reported only from "virgin" areas or on the edge of endemic areas, following the introduction of infected vector arthropods. In Australia, the virus is endemic in the northern parts of the country, which are rather identical with the geographic distribution of the vector. Occasional outbreaks, sometimes of big dimensions, occur in southern Australia when conditions are favorable for infected vectors to spread, in certain years and in certain climatic conditions, from endemic to neighbouring, "clean" areas. Therefore, vaccination in Australia is generally limited to susceptible cattle in those border areas or to susceptible animals which have to be introduced into the endemically infected region.

It deserves also to be borne in mind that while the Akabane virus is regarded to be transmitted by vectors exclusively, there is preliminary, experimental evidence (pending further study) that SBV in Europe may be transmitted in semen as well.

In Poland, it was suspected that bulls, imported from an SBV-infected country, have introduced the virus into a receptive area by means of local potent vectors (20130121.1508180).

Several factors, including the SBV-vector profile, their distribution, and the determination of the SBV endemic territories as well as "receptive" areas where the vector is present but the virus not (yet), deserve to be clarified if vaccination is considered. - Mod.AS.]
